The remnants of the last Caribbean storm, Hurricane Bertha, struck the UK a fortnight ago causing dramatic downpours and some flash flooding.

But the tail-end of Cristobal is likely to veer north and miss us, sucking a warm air mass up from Spain and creating at least a few days of dry weather.

It will come as a relief after a sodden Bank Holiday weekend and a bitterly cold week.

Hurricane Cristobal, which last night whipped across the Caribbean at 75mph and dumped 4 inches (10cm) of rain on Bermuda, is expected to move up the east coast of the United States before hurtling across the Atlantic.

Though showing a similar path to ex-Hurricane Bertha which caused havoc at the beginning of August, it is not expected to have anywhere near the same impact on Britain’s weather when it arrives at the weekend.

According to America’s National Hurricane Centre, Cristobal will weaken to a storm as it moves towards Europe on Sunday. 

